Note:
This file provides CORE string operations needed by Layer 0 and Layer 1 primitives.

These are the absolute minimum string functions needed for:
- sizeof.runa (string_equals for type name comparison)
- offsetof.runa (string_equals for field name lookup)
- Any other primitive that needs basic string comparison

This is Layer 1 because it depends ONLY on memory_core.runa

Higher-level string operations (concat, duplicate, etc.) belong in
core/string_primitive.runa (Layer 2).

Depends on: memory_core.runa (for byte access), memory/layout.runa (for the
owned-heap allocator used by string_duplicate)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Basic String Operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "string_length" takes str as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Goal: compute the length of a null-terminated string in a way that
        is robust against parser-precedence variation. The natural form
        (While memory_get_byte(str, len) is not equal to 0) was historically
        mis-parsed by some bootstrap parser versions, which bound the
        "is not equal to 0" comparison as a second argument to
        memory_get_byte rather than as a comparison applied to the call's
        result. That mis-parse produced an infinite loop the moment user
        code called the convenience print path, since the body of the loop
        scanned past every byte while the condition read a boolean rather
        than a byte. Binding the call result to an explicit local before
        testing it makes the lowering identical across all parser versions.
        See DEV-LOG #115 root cause #2 for the disassembly proof.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard returning 0.
            2. Initialize len to 0 and a scanning flag to 1.
            3. Loop while scanning equals 1:
                 a. Read a single byte at str+len via memory_get_byte and
                    bind it to byte_value. This call appears alone on its
                    own statement; no trailing comparison can attach to it.
                 b. If byte_value is 0, clear scanning to terminate the loop.
                 c. Otherwise, increment len and continue.
            4. Return the final len, which counts bytes before the terminator.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        O(n) in string length. One memory_get_byte call per byte plus one
        compare-branch. The explicit-local idiom adds zero runtime cost
        over the inline form - the compiler lowers Let byte_value to a
        single load that would have happened anyway. The advantage is
        purely parser-correctness; the generated code is equivalent under
        a correct parser.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Caller controls str pointer. NULL is explicitly rejected. Non-NULL
        pointers are assumed to point at a null-terminated buffer the caller
        owns; this function will read forward until it finds a zero byte,
        so callers MUST guarantee null termination - an unterminated buffer
        will cause this function to walk past the end of the allocated region,
        which is a use-after-bounds class fault on the caller's side.
    @End Security_Scope

    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let len be 0
    Let scanning be 1
    While scanning is equal to 1:
        Let byte_value be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, len
        If byte_value is equal to 0:
            Set scanning to 0
        Otherwise:
            Set len to len plus 1
        End If
    End While

    Return len
End Process

Process called "string_char_at" takes str as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get character (byte value) at specified index in string
    Note: Returns byte value at position, or 0 if index is out of bounds or str is NULL
    Note: No bounds checking - caller must ensure index is valid

    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL pointer
    End If

    If index is less than 0:
        Return 0  Note: Negative index invalid
    End If

    Note: Get byte at position using memory_get_byte
    Let byte_value be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, index
    Return byte_value
End Process

Process called "char_to_string" takes char_code as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Goal: materialise a single Unicode code point as a fresh
        NUL-terminated UTF-8 string. This is the write-direction
        counterpart of string_char_at: lexers and translation frontends
        accumulate decoded characters one at a time and need a heap
        string suitable for concatenation. Multiple frontends grew their
        own copies of this encoder (or called a nonexistent
        string_from_char); this is the single canonical export, ruled
        into StringCore by owner decision on task #465.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Validates the code point first per RFC 3629: negative values,
        values above U+10FFFF, and UTF-16 surrogate halves
        (U+D800..U+DFFF, illegal in UTF-8) are replaced with U+FFFD
        REPLACEMENT CHARACTER. Then encodes by range: 1 byte below
        U+0080, 2 bytes below U+0800, 3 bytes below U+10000, 4 bytes up
        to U+10FFFF. Each buffer is allocated with one extra byte for
        the NUL terminator via the canonical owned-heap allocator
        (allocate from Layout). Shift and mask amounts are computed in
        dedicated locals so Runa operator precedence (shift binds weaker
        than plus/minus) can never regroup the expressions.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Allocates 2 to 5 bytes on the owned heap; returns 0 only if the
        allocator fails. The result is always NUL-terminated and the
        caller owns the buffer (release via the Layout deallocator).
        Invalid input never produces an out-of-range write: every code
        point is clamped to U+FFFD before any byte arithmetic, so the
        emitted bytes are always a well-formed UTF-8 sequence.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Replace invalid code points with U+FFFD
    If char_code is less than 0:
        Set char_code to 65533
    End If
    If char_code is greater than 1114111:
        Set char_code to 65533
    End If
    If char_code is greater than or equal to 55296 and char_code is less than or equal to 57343:
        Set char_code to 65533
    End If

    Note: 1-byte sequence: U+0000..U+007F
    If char_code is less than 128:
        Let buf1 be proc allocate from Layout with 2
        If buf1 is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf1, 0, char_code
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf1, 1, 0
        Return buf1
    End If

    Note: 2-byte sequence: U+0080..U+07FF
    If char_code is less than 2048:
        Let hi2 be char_code shifted right by 6
        Let lo2 be char_code bitwise and 63
        Let buf2 be proc allocate from Layout with 3
        If buf2 is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf2, 0, 192 plus hi2
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf2, 1, 128 plus lo2
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf2, 2, 0
        Return buf2
    End If

    Note: 3-byte sequence: U+0800..U+FFFF
    If char_code is less than 65536:
        Let hi3 be char_code shifted right by 12
        Let mid3_shifted be char_code shifted right by 6
        Let mid3 be mid3_shifted bitwise and 63
        Let lo3 be char_code bitwise and 63
        Let buf3 be proc allocate from Layout with 4
        If buf3 is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf3, 0, 224 plus hi3
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf3, 1, 128 plus mid3
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf3, 2, 128 plus lo3
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf3, 3, 0
        Return buf3
    End If

    Note: 4-byte sequence: U+10000..U+10FFFF
    Let b1 be char_code shifted right by 18
    Let b2_shifted be char_code shifted right by 12
    Let b2 be b2_shifted bitwise and 63
    Let b3_shifted be char_code shifted right by 6
    Let b3 be b3_shifted bitwise and 63
    Let b4 be char_code bitwise and 63
    Let buf4 be proc allocate from Layout with 5
    If buf4 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf4, 0, 240 plus b1
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf4, 1, 128 plus b2
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf4, 2, 128 plus b3
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf4, 3, 128 plus b4
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf4, 4, 0
    Return buf4
End Process

Process called "string_equals" takes str1 as Integer, str2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compare two strings for equality
    Note: Returns 1 if equal, 0 if not equal

    If str1 is equal to 0:
        If str2 is equal to 0:
            Return 1  Note: Both NULL
        End If
        Return 0  Note: One NULL
    End If

    If str2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: One NULL
    End If

    Note: Compare byte by byte until null terminator or mismatch
    Let i be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let byte1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str1, i
        Let byte2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str2, i

        If byte1 is not equal to byte2:
            Return 0  Note: Mismatch
        End If

        If byte1 is equal to 0:
            Return 1  Note: Both strings ended, they're equal
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0  Note: Should never reach here
End Process

Process called "string_compare" takes str1 as Integer, str2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compare two strings lexicographically
    Note: Returns: -1 if str1 < str2, 0 if equal, 1 if str1 > str2

    If str1 is equal to 0:
        If str2 is equal to 0:
            Return 0  Note: Both NULL
        End If
        Return -1  Note: NULL is less than non-NULL
    End If

    If str2 is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: non-NULL is greater than NULL
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let byte1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str1, i
        Let byte2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str2, i

        If byte1 is less than byte2:
            Return -1
        End If

        If byte1 is greater than byte2:
            Return 1
        End If

        If byte1 is equal to 0:
            Return 0  Note: Equal and both ended
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "string_starts_with" takes str as Integer, prefix as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if string starts with prefix
    Note: Returns 1 if str starts with prefix, 0 otherwise

    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If prefix is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: Empty prefix matches everything
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let prefix_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with prefix, i

        If prefix_byte is equal to 0:
            Return 1  Note: Reached end of prefix, match!
        End If

        Let str_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, i

        If str_byte is not equal to prefix_byte:
            Return 0  Note: Mismatch
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "string_ends_with" takes str as Integer, suffix as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if string ends with suffix
    Note: Returns 1 if str ends with suffix, 0 otherwise

    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If suffix is equal to 0:
        Return 1  Note: Empty suffix matches everything
    End If

    Let str_len be proc string_length with str
    Let suffix_len be proc string_length with suffix

    If suffix_len is greater than str_len:
        Return 0  Note: Suffix longer than string
    End If

    Note: Compare from the end
    Let offset be str_len minus suffix_len
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than suffix_len:
        Let str_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, offset plus i
        Let suffix_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with suffix, i

        If str_byte is not equal to suffix_byte:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "string_copy_to_buffer" takes src as Integer, dest as Integer, dest_offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Copy source string to destination buffer at specified offset
    Note: Does NOT add null terminator - caller must handle that
    Note: Returns number of bytes copied
    Note: Used for building composite strings in error messages

    If src is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL source
    End If

    If dest is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: NULL destination
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let byte_value be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with src, i

        If byte_value is equal to 0:
            Note: Reached null terminator, done copying
            Return i
        End If

        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with dest, dest_offset plus i, byte_value
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return i
End Process

@Reasoning:
    Goal: provide the canonical "wrap a string literal as a String" primitive.
    Runa string literals are emitted by the compiler as pointers to
    null-terminated immutable byte sequences in the read-only data segment;
    a String at the Runa-source level is precisely such a pointer. The
    canonical name create_from_literal exists so that callers reading their
    own code see "create a String from this literal" as an explicit
    abstraction, even though the underlying representation is the identity
    transform. Every consumer (LIR register-name lookups, optimization-pass
    metadata producers, error-message builders) calls this rather than
    referring to the literal pointer directly so the data model can later
    evolve toward owned, refcounted, or interned String representations
    without changing call sites.

    The string literal passed in is already a pointer to a static
    null-terminated buffer owned by the read-only segment, so no allocation
    is needed: returning the literal pointer yields a fully-valid String
    that the caller can pass to every other String operation in this module
    and in higher layers. The returned pointer is shared with every other
    consumer of the same literal (literals with identical contents are
    pooled by the compiler at emission time), so callers MUST NOT mutate
    its contents and MUST NOT free it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
    Steps:
        1. Accept the literal_ptr argument; the compiler has already
           lowered the source-level literal into a pointer to the static
           data segment by the time control reaches here.
        2. Return literal_ptr unchanged. The Runa String representation is
           the null-terminated byte pointer, so the literal already IS a
           valid String.
    Null input returns 0, matching the behavior of every other StringCore
    primitive when handed a null pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
    O(1). Inlines to a single mov (return-argument forwarding) on every
    target architecture. No allocation, no copy, no work whatsoever beyond
    the call/return overhead — which the compiler eliminates via
    cross-module inlining for the common case where the caller is in the
    same compilation unit.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
    Literal pointer must be a valid null-terminated buffer; the compiler
    enforces this at lowering time by emitting literals into the read-only
    data segment. A null input returns 0 (the documented null sentinel).
    No allocation, no writes, no side effects.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "create_from_literal" takes literal_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If literal_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return literal_ptr
End Process

Process called "string_duplicate" takes str as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocates a fresh owned copy of a null-terminated string. Returns
    Note: pointer to the new buffer or 0 on failure (null input or alloc fail).
    Note: Callers must release via Memory.memory_free.
    Note: ============================================================
    Note: Bug fix: hashtable_set called `proc string_duplicate from String`
    Note: but String (=string_core) had no such Process. The Bug #419
    Note: fallback resolved the call to compiler/internal/string_utils'
    Note: string_duplicate, which expects an owned-buffer struct (offset 0
    Note: = data_ptr, 8 = length, 16 = capacity), not a null-terminated
    Note: C-style string. The mismatch made hashtable_set return 0 for
    Note: every new key, breaking every Dict/HashSet primitive at runtime.
    Note: Exposing the correct C-style duplicator here resolves the call
    Note: through alias-disambiguated lookup before the fallback runs.
    Note: ============================================================
    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let len be string_length(str)
    Let buf be proc allocate from Layout with len plus 1
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, i
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf, i, b
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with buf, len, 0
    Return buf
End Process
